              </entry>
            </row>
          </tbody>
        </tgroup>
      </informaltable>
      <para>
        All packages containing binary files have the corresponding
        <literal>-debuginfo</literal> packages.
      </para>
      <para>
        For server installations, you need
        <literal>postgrespro-&majorversion;-server</literal>.
        For a minimal client installation, only the
        <literal>libpq5.9</literal> package is required.
        <literal>postgrespro-&majorversion;</literal> is typically needed on
        clients.
      </para>
      <para>
        <application>pg_config</application> utility is only
        shipped as part of <literal>postgrespro-&majorversion;-devel</literal>
        package, so you need to install this package if you are going to
        compile client programs that use <application>pg_config</application> in
        the build process.
      </para>
    </sect3>
    <sect3>
      <title>Installing Multiple <productname>&productname;</productname> Instances</title>
      <para>
        On ALT Linux, you can only have a single PostgreSQL installation
        on your system at a time. If you are installing a newer version
        over the old one, new binaries replace the old ones. To perform
        database upgrade using
        <filename>pg_upgrade</filename> utility, you need
        both new and old <literal>postgres</literal>
        executable files. So, preinstallation script copies the existing
        <literal>postgres</literal> binary and
        <literal>libpq</literal> shared library into
        <filename>/usr/lib64/pgsql/&majorversion;/backup</filename>. Use this
        directory name as an argument of the
        <filename>pg_upgrade</filename>
        <literal>-b</literal> option.
      </para>
    </sect3>
  </sect2>
