    <sect3>
      <title>Creating the Default Database</title>
      <para>
        To start Postgres server after installation of the server
        package, run the following command:
      </para>
      <programlisting>
service postgresql start
</programlisting>
      <para>
        The default database in SUSE is created upon the first start of
        service. You can customize its location, locale, and other
        parameters in <filename>/etc/sysconfig/postgrespro</filename>.
      </para>
    </sect3>
    <sect3>
      <title>Installing Multiple <productname>&productname;</productname> Instances</title>
      <para>
        On SUSE systems, you cannot install several versions of client
        programs simultaneously.
      </para>
    </sect3>
  </sect2>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="binary-installation-on-windows">
  <title>Installing <productname>&productname;</productname> on Windows</title>
  <para>
    For Windows systems, <productname>&productname;</productname> provides a binary self-extracting
    interactive installer that installs all the components at once. The
    installer also provides the options to create the default database.
  </para>
  <sect2 id="external-connections-and-windows-firewall">
    <title>External Connections and Windows Firewall</title>
    <para>
      By default, <productname>&productname;</productname> server is listening for connections from the
      localhost only. To allow external connections to <productname>&productname;</productname>
      server, select the &quot;Allow external connections&quot; checkbox
      to add the appropriate parameter into the
      <literal>postgresql.conf</literal> file, add a line into the
      <literal>pg_pba.conf</literal> file, and create a Windows Firewall
      rule.
    </para>
    <note><para>
      <productname>&productname;</productname> application is registered with Windows
      firewal anyway, so if you haven't enabled external connection
      during installation, and decide to do it later, you only have to
      open Windows Firewall configuration in the Control Panel, find the
      <productname>&productname;</productname> server here, and allow it to accept connections.
    </para>
    </note>
  </sect2>
  <sect2 id="supported-operating-systems">
    <title>Supported Operating Systems</title>
    <para>
      <productname>&productname;</productname> provides two versions of Windows distribution:
    </para>
    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
      <listitem>
        <para>
          distribution for Windows 7, Windows Server 2008 R2 or higher
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          compatibility distribution built with Windows SDK 7.1, which
          supports Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 Do not use the
          compatibility version on newer versions of Windows.
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </sect2>
  <sect2 id="procedural-languages">
    <title>Procedural Languages</title>
    <para>
      The procedural languages <literal>PL/Perl</literal>,
      <literal>PL/Python</literal> are included in this distribution of
      <productname>&productname;</productname>. The server has been built using the LanguagePack
      community distributions of those language interpreters. To use any
      of the these languages from within <productname>&productname;</productname>, download and
      install the appropriate interpreters and ensure they are included
      in the <literal>PATH</literal> variable under which the database
      server will be started.
      <!-- The versions used are shown below - newer
      minor (bugfix) releases may also work, but have not been tested. -->
    </para>
    <para>
      The current version of <literal>PL/Python</literal> is dynamically
      linked with Python shared library in the LanguagePack installers.
      Some distributions of Python interpreters (including ActivePython)
      on Windows do not include a dynamic library of Python. Such
      interpreters would no longer be functional with
      <literal>PL/Python</literal>. You are recommended to use
      LanguagePack installers for <literal>PL/Perl</literal> and
      <literal>PL/Python</literal> instead.
    </para>
  </sect2>
  <sect2 id="windows-service-account">
    <title>Windows Service Account</title>
    <para>
      A special <literal>NT AUTHORITY\\NetworkService</literal>
      account is used.
    </para>
  </sect2>
  <sect2 id="command-line-options">
    <title>Command-Line Options</title>
    <para>
      Installation directory path:
    </para>
    <programlisting>
/D=<replaceable>path</replaceable>
</programlisting>
    <para>
      Silent install:
    </para>
    <programlisting>
/S
</programlisting>
    <para>
      <literal>*.ini</literal> file with instalation options:
    </para>
    <programlisting>
/init=<replaceable>ini_file_name</replaceable>
</programlisting>
  </sect2>
  <sect2 id="ini-file-format">
    <title>INI File Format</title>
    <para>
      In the section [options] can be these options:
    </para>
    <itemizedlist spacing="compact">
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>InstallDir</literal> &mdash; path where to install server
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>DataDir</literal> &mdash; path where to create default
          database
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>Port</literal> &mdash; TCP/IP port to listen (5432)
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>SuperUser</literal> &mdash; name of the database user who
          has admin rights in the database
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>Password</literal> &mdash; password of the user
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>noExtConnections = 1</literal> &mdash; don't allow external
          connection
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>Coding = UNICODE</literal> &mdash; character encoding to
          use in the database
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>Locale</literal> &mdash; locale to use in the database.
          There can be several different locales for each encoding
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>Vcredist = no</literal> &mdash; do not install Visual C
          redistributable libraries (use it only if these libraries are
          already installed on your system)
        </para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <literal>envvar = 1</literal> &mdash; set up environment variables
          helpful for <productname>&productname;</productname>: <literal>PGDATA</literal>,
          <literal>PGDATABASE</literal>, <literal>PGUSER</literal>,
          <literal>PGPORT</literal>, <literal>PGLOCALEDIR</literal>
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </sect2>
</sect1>
<sect1 id="installing-additional-modules">
  <title>Installing Additional Supplied Modules</title>
  <para>
    <productname>&productname;</productname> comes with a huge set of server extensions, or modules.
    On Windows, these extensions are always installed. On Linux, they
    are included into the <literal>postgrespro-contrib</literal> package
    which may or may not be installed. If it is installed, you already
    have binary files for these extensions in the system and only need
    to enable it in the database in order to use it.
  </para>
  <para>
    Typically, you only need to issue the following SQL command:
  </para>
  <programlisting>
CREATE EXTENSION <replaceable>module_name</replaceable>
</programlisting>
<para>For details, see <xref linkend="sql-createextension">.
</para>
  <para>
    To get the list of extensions available in your <productname>&productname;</productname>
    installation, view the
    <link linkend="view-pg-available-extensions"><structname>pg_available_extensions</structname></link>
    system catalog.
  </para>
  <para>
    <xref linkend="contrib"> contains documentation
    for extensions available in the installation.
  </para>
  <para>
    Some extensions require shared libraries to be preloaded on server
    startup.
  </para>
  <para>
    If you want to use such an extension, you need to add parameter
  </para>
  <programlisting>
shared_preload_libraries = '<replaceable>lib1</replaceable>, <replaceable>lib2</replaceable>, <replaceable>lib3</replaceable>'
</programlisting>
  <para>
    into <filename>postgresql.conf</filename> of your
    <productname>&productname;</productname> database
    instance and restart the server. After that you can issue the
    <literal>CREATE EXTENSION</literal> statement.
  </para>
</sect1>
</chapter>
